member.name: T:OSMaker.Loader.BasicHostLoader
member.summary: Inherits from BasicDesignerLoader. It can persist the HostSurface to an Xml file and can also parse the Xml file to re-create the RootComponent and all the components that it hosts.

members.member: Empty constructor simply creates a new form.

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.BasicHostLoader.#ctor(System.String)
member.summary: This constructor takes a file name. This file should exist on disk and consist of XML that can be read by a data set.

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.BasicHostLoader.PerformFlush(System.ComponentModel.Design.Serialization.IDesignerSerializationManager)
member.summary: This method is called by the designer host whenever it wants the designer loader to flush any pending changes. Flushing changes does not mean the same thing as saving to disk. For example, In Visual Studio, flushing changes causes new code to be generated and inserted into the text editing window. The user can edit the new code in the editing window, but nothing has been saved to disk. This sample adheres to this separation between flushing and saving, since a flush occurs whenever the code windows are displayed or there is a build. Neither of those items demands a save.

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.BasicHostLoader.GetConversionSupported(System.ComponentModel.TypeConverter,System.Type)
member.summary: Simple helper method that returns true if the given type converter supports two-way conversion of the given type.

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.BasicHostLoader.OnComponentChanged(System.Object,System.ComponentModel.Design.ComponentChangedEventArgs)
member.summary: As soon as things change, we're dirty, so Flush()ing will give us a new xmlDocument and codeCompileUnit.

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.BasicHostLoader.PromptDispose
member.summary: This method prompts the user to see if it is OK to dispose this document. The prompt only happens if the user has made changes.

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.BasicHostLoader.PerformFlushWorker
member.summary: This will recussively go through all the objects in the tree and serialize them to Xml

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.BasicHostLoader.ReadFile(System.String,System.Collections.ArrayList,System.Xml.XmlDocument@)
member.summary:
This method is used to parse the given file. Before calling this method the host member variable must be setup. This method will create a data set, read the data set from the XML stored in the file, and then walk through the data set and create components stored within it. The data set is stored in the persistedData member variable upon return.
This method never throws exceptions. It will set the successful ref parameter to false when there are catastrophic errors it can't resolve (like being unable to parse the XML). All error exceptions are added to the errors array list, including minor errors.

members.member: Reads the "Object" tags. This returns an instance of the newly created object. Returns null if there was an error.
Parses the given XML node and sets the resulting property value.
Generic function to read an object value. Returns true if the read succeeded.
This method writes out the contents of our designer in XML. It writes out the contents of xmlDocument.

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.BasicHostLoader.Save(System.Boolean)
member.summary: Save the current state of the loader. If the user loaded the file or saved once before, then he doesn't need to select a file again. Unless this is being called as a result of "Save As..." being clicked, in which case forceFilePrompt will be true.

member.name: T:OSMaker.Loader.CodeDomHostLoader
member.summary: Inherits from CodeDomDesignerLoader. It can generate C# or VB code for a HostSurface. This loader does not support parsing a C# or VB file.

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.CodeDomHostLoader.Parse
member.summary: Bootstrap method - loads a blank Form

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.CodeDomHostLoader.Write(System.CodeDom.CodeCompileUnit)
member.summary: When the Loader is Flushed this method is called. The base class (CodeDomDesignerLoader) creates the CodeCompileUnit. We simply cache it and use this when we need to generate code from it. To generate the code we use CodeProvider.

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.CodeDomHostLoader.GetCodeCompileUnit
member.summary: Flushes the host and returns the updated CodeCompileUnit

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.CodeDomHostLoader.GetCode(System.String)
member.summary: This method writes out the contents of our designer in C# and VB. It generates code from our codeCompileUnit using CodeRpovider

member.summary: Called when we want to build an executable. Returns true if we succeeded.

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.CodeDomHostLoader.Run
member.summary: Here we build the executable and then run it. We make sure to not start two of the same process.

member.name: M:OSMaker.Loader.CodeDomHostLoader.Stop
member.summary: Just in case the red X in the upper right isn't good enough, we can kill our process here.
